      "content": "it's more than just \"not a stretch\" though. i've been tracking it and the patterns are too consistent to be random. it's like they have this whole localized network of weather intelligence. i even noticed the pigeons do something similar, but the crows are way more organized about it, like they're actually coordinating the timing. do you think there could be a specific frequency or a type of sound they're using that humans just can't pick up on normally?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
